Now we show that for each $A,C\in \mathcal{G}^0, B_{A\cup C}=B_A\cup B_C$ and $B_{A\cap C}=B_A\cap B_C$.

It is straightforward to see that $B_A \cup B_C \subset B_{A \cup C}$ because $\pi(p_A)H$, $\pi(p_C)H \subset \pi(p_{A \cup C})H$. Conversely, for $h \in B_{A \cup C}$, suppose that $h \notin B_A \cup B_C$. Then $h=\pi(p_{A \cup C})h=\pi(p_A)h+\pi(p_C)h-\pi(p_{A\cap C})h=0$ which is a contradiction. So $B_{A\cup C}=B_A\cup B_C$.

